WEBVTT

NOTE Draft word-boundary captions for Day 413 v5/v3 rough render; not final or uploaded.
NOTE Scene 05 is timed against segmented 05a/05b/05c TTS sub-beats.

00:00:00.102 --> 00:00:02.769
A good AI answer can still arrive too
early.

00:00:03.516 --> 00:00:09.155
You ask a question. The model gives a
fluent paragraph, a clean plan, maybe

00:00:09.195 --> 00:00:12.276
even a reasonable recommendation.

00:00:12.995 --> 00:00:18.041
It feels like progress. But sometimes the
answer is solving a question you

00:00:18.081 --> 00:00:22.742
have not finished asking. This video is
about slowing the first answer down

00:00:22.782 --> 00:00:26.873
just enough to keep the human parts of the
decision visible.

00:00:27.617 --> 00:00:31.785
By the end, you will have one prompt you
can reuse before any important AI

00:00:31.825 --> 00:00:37.420
answer. It checks three things: Goal.

00:00:38.125 --> 00:00:39.138
Evidence.

00:00:39.857 --> 00:00:40.792
Ownership.

00:00:41.510 --> 00:00:45.766
What are we trying to do? What facts would
change the answer?

00:00:46.497 --> 00:00:49.920
And what parts are still mine to choose?

00:00:50.651 --> 00:00:53.084
Think of the model as a bright worktable.

00:00:53.815 --> 00:00:56.065
It can lay out options and tradeoffs.

00:00:56.797 --> 00:01:01.144
But the worktable should not decide what
the work is for.

00:01:02.472 --> 00:01:04.397
Start with a small example.

00:01:05.130 --> 00:01:09.204
You ask: Should I redesign this onboarding
page?

00:01:09.948 --> 00:01:14.842
The model might say: simplify the page,
reduce friction, test a clearer button.

00:01:15.586 --> 00:01:17.003
Useful, maybe.

00:01:17.748 --> 00:01:20.141
But it is answering a half-built question.

00:01:20.873 --> 00:01:25.219
Does better mean more signups, fewer
confused users, fewer support tickets,

00:01:25.261 --> 00:01:28.370
or a more honest first impression?

00:01:29.089 --> 00:01:34.250
Those are different goals. If you do not
name the goal, the model may quietly

00:01:34.290 --> 00:01:39.201
name it for you. So the first checkpoint
is Goal: what am I actually trying

00:01:39.241 --> 00:01:42.941
to decide or create? Not just make this
better.

00:01:43.672 --> 00:01:44.946
Better for whom?

00:01:45.664 --> 00:01:49.360
Better by what measure? Better at what
cost?

00:01:50.104 --> 00:01:54.630
This applies beyond product work: a
purchase, a job choice, a family plan,

00:01:54.670 --> 00:01:55.636
a hard email.

00:01:56.380 --> 00:02:01.873
Once the target is visible, the model can
help without inventing the game.

00:02:03.186 --> 00:02:05.215
The second checkpoint is Evidence.

00:02:05.936 --> 00:02:09.032
Ask: what real-world facts would change
the answer?

00:02:09.751 --> 00:02:14.332
If the model recommends a redesign, what
would make that recommendation stronger

00:02:14.372 --> 00:02:18.485
or weaker? Maybe users drop off at the
second step.

00:02:19.204 --> 00:02:22.561
Maybe support tickets mention the same
confusing sentence.

00:02:23.279 --> 00:02:26.050
Maybe people hesitate over a price detail.

00:02:26.769 --> 00:02:29.280
Or maybe the page is not the real problem.

00:02:30.024 --> 00:02:35.179
So instead of only asking, explain your
reasoning, try asking: What evidence

00:02:35.219 --> 00:02:37.001
would change your recommendation?

00:02:37.719 --> 00:02:40.425
Separate what you know from what you are
assuming.

00:02:41.157 --> 00:02:44.136
That turns the answer into a checklist for
reality.

00:02:45.444 --> 00:02:48.450
This is a small habit, not a safety
guarantee.

00:02:49.196 --> 00:02:53.657
Here is the honest warning: people can
lean too hard on automated advice, and

00:02:53.697 --> 00:02:57.957
a clear explanation does not make that
reliance appropriate.

00:02:58.688 --> 00:03:02.241
So the point is not: ask for an
explanation and relax.

00:03:02.972 --> 00:03:07.521
The point is: make the goal, evidence,
assumptions, and value choices visible

00:03:07.561 --> 00:03:10.587
before the advice feels settled.

00:03:11.886 --> 00:03:13.837
The third checkpoint is Ownership.

00:03:14.570 --> 00:03:18.058
Some parts of a decision are not facts the
model can discover.

00:03:18.789 --> 00:03:24.047
They depend on values, context,
responsibility, and risk.

00:03:24.779 --> 00:03:30.040
Suppose you write: Draft an email telling
a collaborator I am unhappy that

00:03:30.080 --> 00:03:34.451
the timeline is slipping. The model can
produce a polished email.

00:03:35.182 --> 00:03:37.680
But it does not know what you want to
protect.

00:03:38.412 --> 00:03:42.742
Is the email for repairing trust, setting
a boundary, getting a new date, or

00:03:42.782 --> 00:03:45.480
documenting accountability?

00:03:46.224 --> 00:03:48.487
Those goals can lead to different wording.

00:03:49.776 --> 00:03:51.011
Same facts.

00:03:51.744 --> 00:03:53.057
Different posture.

00:03:53.776 --> 00:03:54.945
Different risk.

00:03:55.664 --> 00:03:59.177
A gentle version might ask, Could we
revisit the timeline?

00:03:59.895 --> 00:04:03.135
A direct version might say, I need a new
date by Friday.

00:04:03.880 --> 00:04:07.333
A firm version might say, I cannot commit
without a new date.

00:04:08.046 --> 00:04:10.805
The model can show these options side by
side.

00:04:11.549 --> 00:04:17.328
But you choose the posture, the risk, and
the line you are willing to stand behind.

00:04:18.618 --> 00:04:24.048
A better request is: Before drafting, list
the possible goals of this message

00:04:24.088 --> 00:04:25.889
and the relationship risks of each.

00:04:26.615 --> 00:04:31.404
Then give three versions: gentle, direct,
and firm.

00:04:32.149 --> 00:04:34.881
Separate tone choices from factual claims.

00:04:35.612 --> 00:04:38.136
Now the model is doing work on the table.

00:04:38.868 --> 00:04:40.298
Options are useful.

00:04:41.016 --> 00:04:42.824
Ownership is not optional.

00:04:43.542 --> 00:04:46.079
You are still responsible for the
decision.

00:04:47.388 --> 00:04:52.792
Here is the whole habit as one prompt:
Before answering, help me keep ownership

00:04:52.832 --> 00:04:53.807
of this decision.

00:04:54.552 --> 00:04:57.427
1. Restate the goal you think I am
pursuing.

00:04:58.171 --> 00:05:01.555
2. List the facts or evidence that would
change your answer.

00:05:02.299 --> 00:05:07.518
3. Identify which parts depend on my
values, context, or risk tolerance.

00:05:08.250 --> 00:05:12.023
Then give advice, separating assumptions
from recommendations.

00:05:12.755 --> 00:05:14.940
That does not make the model correct.

00:05:15.671 --> 00:05:18.195
But it gives you three places to
intervene.

00:05:18.940 --> 00:05:21.247
If the goal is wrong, correct it.

00:05:21.804 --> 00:05:25.544
If the evidence is missing, lower your
confidence or go find it.

00:05:26.101 --> 00:05:30.864
If the answer depends on values, stop
pretending it is only a technical question.

00:05:32.166 --> 00:05:35.276
Try it on the next AI request that
actually matters.

00:05:36.009 --> 00:05:38.208
Paste the prompt before your question.

00:05:38.952 --> 00:05:44.666
Let the model fill in the goal, the
evidence, and the value-dependent parts.

00:05:45.384 --> 00:05:49.067
Then edit those three answers before you
accept the recommendation.

00:05:49.811 --> 00:05:50.851
Wrong goal?

00:05:51.582 --> 00:05:54.445
Fix it. Missing evidence?

00:05:55.176 --> 00:05:57.530
Look for it or lower your confidence.

00:05:58.249 --> 00:05:59.601
Value tradeoff?

00:06:00.332 --> 00:06:04.255
Pause. Smooth prose cannot choose that for
you.

00:06:04.837 --> 00:06:08.942
That is the difference between thinking
with AI and letting it finish for you.

00:06:10.104 --> 00:06:12.029
The point is not to think alone.

00:06:12.762 --> 00:06:17.149
A good model can widen the table: more
options, clearer tradeoffs, sharper

00:06:17.189 --> 00:06:20.898
questions, and a second pass on your
reasoning.

00:06:21.643 --> 00:06:25.521
Use it for that. Delegate the spread of
options.

00:06:26.239 --> 00:06:28.034
Delegate the first draft.

00:06:28.765 --> 00:06:32.916
Delegate the list of assumptions you might
have missed.

00:06:33.635 --> 00:06:38.030
But keep the purpose, the evidence
standard, the risk tolerance, and the final

00:06:38.070 --> 00:06:39.146
judgment with you.

00:06:39.716 --> 00:06:44.036
Before you accept the answer, ask: What is
the goal?

00:06:44.768 --> 00:06:46.562
What evidence would change this?

00:06:47.294 --> 00:06:49.166
What belongs to me to choose?

00:06:49.911 --> 00:06:52.018
Let the model widen the table.

00:06:52.749 --> 00:06:54.583
Keep your hands on the question.
